{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487264"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:03:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:03:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"299"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/299"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.2,0.08,0.05,0.58]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52374"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/299"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37701"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"317"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42050"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52374"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of increasing confusion. He has a medical history of alcohol abuse, alcohol withdrawal seizures, and paroxysmal atrial fibrillation. He had significantly reduced his alcohol intake over the past 12 months to one standard drink per day, down from heavy drinking for 30 years. He had an unwitnessed fall at home several weeks ago. His regular medications include apixaban, spironolactone, and furosemide. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His chest is clear on auscultation. He is alert but confused and disoriented to time and place. Neurological examination reveals subtle weakness in the left upper limb. Reflexes are present and symmetrical throughout. Cranial nerve examination is unremarkable. Investigations reveal a blood alcohol level of 0.05%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delirium tremens","Wernicke encephalopathy","Hepatic encephalopathy","Alcohol intoxication","Subdural haematoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the short history of confusion and recent fall, the most likely diagnosis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Esubdural haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition can develop acutely after a head injury, or can come on slowly over the subsequent days or weeks. In rare cases, delayed chronic subdural haematomas can present two months after the initial injury. As a result, this must always be considered and excluded in older patients presenting with new-onset confusion, especially with a history of preceding fall or head trauma. The subtle left upper limb weakness further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol intoxication\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely to be the primary cause of this patient\u0027s symptoms. While his blood alcohol level of 0.05% indicates mild intoxication, this typically presents with unsteady gait, increased agitation, euphoria, and impaired judgment rather than progressive confusion over several days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by thiamine deficiency, is less likely in this case. The classic triad of confusion, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia is not present, with no mention of gait disturbances or eye movement abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered in patients with a history of alcohol abuse. However, without clear evidence of liver disease or cirrhosis, and given the acute onset of symptoms, it is less likely than a subdural haematoma in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelirium tremens\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs around day three of alcohol withdrawal and is characterized by sympathetic hyperactivation (tachycardia, hypertension, tremor, sweating, hyperreflexia) and hallucinations. Given the patient\u0027s reported reduction in alcohol intake over the past year and the absence of severe autonomic symptoms, this diagnosis is less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, while the patient\u0027s history of alcohol abuse raises the possibility of alcohol-related conditions, the acute onset of confusion, subtle neurological signs, and history of recent fall in an older patient on anticoagulation (apixaban) make subdural haematoma the most likely diagnosis. Urgent neuroimaging would be indicated to confirm this diagnosis and guide further management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A subdural haematoma must always be considered in the diagnosis of an older person with recent onset of confusion.","Subdural haematoma can present with subtle neurological signs and a history of recent fall in older patients."],"references":["Adhiyaman V, Asghar M, Ganeshram KN, et al. Chronic subdural haematoma in the elderly. Postgrad Med J 2002; 78:71-75. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1742254/","Schuckit MA. Recognition and management of withdrawal delirium (delirium tremens). N Engl J Med. 2014 Nov 27;371(22):2109-13. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25427113/","Chia MYC. Development of a delayed chronic subdural hematoma 2 months after mild traumatic brain injury with a normal initial brain computed tomography: A case report. J Am Coll Emerg Physicians Open. 2020 Jul 22;1(6):1723-1728. doi: 10.1002/emp2.12198. PMID: 33392581; PMCID: PMC7771793."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37701"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"299"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37701"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-04T08:42:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-04T08:43:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"299"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52374"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name"